00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:30.750
HAZEL SIVE: All
right, moving along,

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:32.975
I want to talk about
three things today.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:48.340
The first is breaking
symmetry in the embryo,

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:51.380
leading to the first
differences that then go on

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:56.060
to amplify into many differences
in a multicellular organism.

00:00:56.060 --> 00:01:05.120
And then I'm going to talk
about organic genesis and then

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:07.670
about morphogenesis.

00:01:07.670 --> 00:01:10.250
And we'll define these
terms as we go along.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:19.755
Let's start with this
question of breaking symmetry.

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:28.260
And I'm going to
start by going back

00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:33.390
to the last handout
of last lecture

00:01:33.390 --> 00:01:35.740
that you should have looked at--

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:41.100
hm, I wonder if our AV
expert could do something

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:41.950
to the screen.

00:01:41.950 --> 00:01:43.320
I don't think it's the computer.

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:44.520
I think it's the screens.

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:45.780
Let's see if we can do this.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:54.790
The last handout I gave
you was a consideration

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:57.732
of how different parts of
the embryo become different.

00:01:57.732 --> 00:02:00.190
And I started off-- and you
might have this in front of you

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:00.690
still--

00:02:00.690 --> 00:02:04.000
I started off with an
embryo, a fertilized egg,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.335
that's got some kind
of asymmetry to it.

00:02:08.335 --> 00:02:12.320
And I've called
it a determinant.

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:15.770
And at the first
cell division, look,

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:18.710
I've put that
determinant into one cell

00:02:18.710 --> 00:02:21.020
and not the other cell.

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:24.500
One cell and not the other cell.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:28.040
Now, let's say that
that determinant has

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.370
some effect on changing
the secreted factors--

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:33.350
oh, fantastic,
thank you very much.

00:02:33.350 --> 00:02:39.970
It's like magic-- that
determinant has an effect.

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:46.090
And it actually elicits signals
to be secreted from the cell.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:48.010
Then look what happens
at the next stage,

00:02:48.010 --> 00:02:51.760
at the four cell stage,
here is a cell that's

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:53.440
secreting a signal.

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:56.850
And it's doing something to the
cell that receives the signal.

00:02:56.850 --> 00:02:58.900
It's making it brown.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:03.010
And that signal in turn
then elicits other signals.

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:04.990
So the brown cells
start signaling

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:06.280
to the cell next door.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:10.810
And as cell division precedes,
you now get gray cell.

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:13.840
And this is a
theoretical, but a real,

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:18.760
demonstration of how the embryo
becomes different over time,

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:21.250
starting with an
initial asymmetry.

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:24.550
That is then built
upon due to segregation

00:03:24.550 --> 00:03:28.990
of localized factors and also
due to cell-cell signaling.

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:31.420
And all of this comes
together to make

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:34.630
these different regions, which
I've cool territories, which

00:03:34.630 --> 00:03:36.460
eventually will
go on to give rise

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:40.750
to different kinds of cells
or different groups of kinds

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:43.140
of cells.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:45.180
If you look in a real embryo--

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:48.729
this is a fruit fly
embryo, Drosophila embryo.

00:03:48.729 --> 00:03:49.770
You don't have a handout.

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:51.100
Just look on the screen.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:53.670
You can see the
sequential division.

00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:56.970
And you can see this by looking
at changes in gene expression

00:03:56.970 --> 00:03:57.640
patterns.

00:03:57.640 --> 00:03:58.890
And it's really spectacular.

00:03:58.890 --> 00:04:00.320
This is a drawing.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.740
But you can actually
look at this

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:03.810
in terms of in
situ hybridization,

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:06.090
that technique I
mentioned last time,

00:04:06.090 --> 00:04:09.190
where one can look at
where RNAs or proteins,

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:11.100
and in the case of in
situ hybridization,

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:14.610
it's RNA, where
RNAs are localized.

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:16.459
And in the very
early embryo, there

00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:18.810
is an asymmetry of
a protein called

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:21.930
bicoid, where there's more
on one side than the other.

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:24.760
A little later,
after fertilization,

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.500
you start to see literally
these stripes of RNA

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:30.870
or protein across the embryo.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:34.080
And then the stripes of
different proteins and RNA

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:39.600
get narrower as the embryo is
divided up into its segments

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:41.440
and so on.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.460
And so what you see out of this
is the embryo being divided up

00:04:45.460 --> 00:04:48.610
from one large territory
into smaller and smaller

00:04:48.610 --> 00:04:49.720
territories.

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:52.225
But the question is,
where does it all start?

00:04:55.710 --> 00:05:06.210
And so the first asymmetry
has got something

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:09.770
to do with fertilization.

00:05:09.770 --> 00:05:27.130
It can either occur before,
at, or after fertilization,

00:05:27.130 --> 00:05:36.010
where the haploid egg and
sperm fuse to become a zygote.

00:05:36.010 --> 00:05:41.930
And somewhere in this process,
this asymmetry develops.

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:45.640
In the case of frogs,
the first asymmetries

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.591
are formed before fertilization,
and also in Drosophila, fruit

00:05:49.591 --> 00:05:50.090
flies.

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:58.820
In the case of
Caenorhabditis, also

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:04.430
known as the worm, asymmetry
forms at fertilization.

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:08.840
And in the case of mammals,
like ourselves, the asymmetries

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:11.010
appear to form of
to fertilization.

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:18.690
And these asymmetries
eventually build up

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.110
to give rise to a system
of positional coordinates,

00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:25.140
kind of like the lines
of latitude and longitude

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:27.280
on the globe.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:47.710
And these are called the axes,
which are positional values.

00:06:47.710 --> 00:06:50.020
And there are three of them.

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:52.540
I'm just going to put the
initials on the board.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:55.720
And then I'll show you a slide,
and you can get these later.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:07:01.360
They're called a
A/P, D/V, and L/R.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:04.450
And if you look on
the screen, you'll

00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:08.230
see my diagram of a mouse,
the same in ourselves,

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:11.710
where there is this
A/P coordinate, which

00:07:11.710 --> 00:07:16.420
stands for anteroposterior,
where antero is the head

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:20.950
and posterior is the tail, or
as far back as your body goes.

00:07:20.950 --> 00:07:25.870
Then there's dorsal which refers
to back and ventral, belly.

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:28.330
And then there's left and right.

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:32.290
And these values are
kind of like north,

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:35.530
south, east, west,
and then degrees

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:38.570
on either side of the meridian.

00:07:38.570 --> 00:07:40.910
They help the embryo
figure out where

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:44.030
to put different organs
in different cell types.

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:46.550
And I'm not going to dwell on
them in the interest of time,

00:07:46.550 --> 00:07:48.110
but there are a
whole sets of genes

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:51.890
that are involved in setting
up these coordinates.

00:07:51.890 --> 00:07:54.890
The one thing that
I will dwell on more

00:07:54.890 --> 00:07:57.050
is a specific
example of setting up

00:07:57.050 --> 00:08:15.210
the first asymmetry
in Caenorhabditis,

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:18.990
where this first asymmetry
is set up at fertilization.

00:08:18.990 --> 00:08:21.480
And the bottom line-- we'll
look on it on your hand out

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:22.620
in a moment--

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:33.419
is that the sperm entry and
particularly the centriole

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:42.010
brought in by the sperm
causes a massive rearrangement

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:46.750
of the cytoskeleton in
the egg or in the zygote.

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:50.710
The cytoskeleton we mentioned
way back in Lecture 2.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:55.930
It is the system of actin,
filaments, and microtubule

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:59.440
tubules that give the
cell shape and allow it,

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:02.890
as we'll discuss later
on, to move and to help

00:09:02.890 --> 00:09:05.800
build the animal or the plant.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:15.050
So this the sperm entry causes
cytoskeletal re-arrangement.

00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:29.730
And this particularly pertains
to actin and tubulin, where

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:36.620
the tubulin forms
microtubules and the actin

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:39.605
forms microfilaments.

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:49.760
And with the cytoskeletal
re-arrangement,

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:53.240
a protein called Par
6, that is firmly

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:57.170
attached to the
cytoskeleton, is pulled

00:09:57.170 --> 00:10:02.200
to one side of the zygote,
leaving one side of the zygote

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:06.240
with lots of par-6 on
the other side with none.

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:10.360
And at the first cell division,
one cell gets lots of Par 6,

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:11.920
and the other gets none.

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:14.290
And that gives you
your first asymmetry

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:16.810
upon which the embryo
builds to give rise

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:19.850
to all its different
cell types and organs.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:25.480
So the cytoskeletal
re-arrangement pulls

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:31.708
the attached Par 6 protein--

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:37.960
and this is a
regulatory protein.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:39.695
It doesn't matter
exactly what it does--

00:10:44.530 --> 00:10:54.060
to the future anterior
side of the embryo.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:57.900
And in doing so, it actually
sets up the anterior side

00:10:57.900 --> 00:10:58.860
of the embryo.

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:02.550
Let's look at your first
slide or your first handout.

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:10.130
This is a diagram of
the early worm egg,

00:11:10.130 --> 00:11:12.260
actually the very
early worm zygote,

00:11:12.260 --> 00:11:16.510
because here is the egg
nucleus, called a pronucleus.

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:18.200
It's haploid.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:21.370
The sperm pronucleus
has just entered.

00:11:21.370 --> 00:11:25.160
And the cytoskeleton I've
represented by this grid.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:29.050
And Par 6 protein is
represented by the red

00:11:29.050 --> 00:11:31.910
that you can see on
the screen surrounding

00:11:31.910 --> 00:11:36.170
the outside of the zygote.

00:11:36.170 --> 00:11:41.120
Here's the sperm entry, causing
cytoskeletal contraction.

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:46.260
And with it, because par-6 is
attached to the cytoskeleton,

00:11:46.260 --> 00:11:50.090
Par 6 is moved to
one side of the cell.

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:52.100
That's the most important thing.

00:11:52.100 --> 00:11:55.760
Later on, the first
cell division along this

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:57.630
dotted line here.

00:11:57.630 --> 00:12:01.040
And you can see that the
first cell, in the first cell

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:04.280
division, one of the cells
would get most of the Par 6

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:07.650
and the other cell
would get very little.

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:09.360
This is a very
beautiful mechanism

00:12:09.360 --> 00:12:13.020
that's been worked out
really beautifully in worms.

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:19.190
Here's a movie that I
guess isn't going to work.

00:12:19.190 --> 00:12:21.020
You know what, it
was working great

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:22.310
before I walked in this room.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:23.490
But it's not going to work.

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:25.870
So I'm going to
post it as a movie.

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:28.710
And you can go to the
URL and you can get it.

00:12:28.710 --> 00:12:30.590
And you'll see what
this movie does

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:33.680
will show you fluorescently
