00:12:51.570 --> 00:12:56.410
Number 2, organogenesis.

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:14.060
An organ, as I've
written on the screen,

00:13:14.060 --> 00:13:17.570
is a functional unit
of many cell types

00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:22.490
that are arranged
obligatorily in

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:24.710
a three-dimensional
structure that allows

00:13:24.710 --> 00:13:27.260
them to function together.

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:32.900
So the problem we have here
is that an organ is many cell

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:46.940
types, arranged in
3-D, such that there

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:51.830
is a specific
functional outcome,

00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:55.940
like the heart pumps blood,
the kidney filters blood,

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:58.280
the eyes see.

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:02.360
All of these things require
both of these correct cell

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:04.670
types and 3-D organization.

00:14:04.670 --> 00:14:08.600
And just this sentence
or just this phrase

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:12.350
raises two questions.

00:14:12.350 --> 00:14:15.200
How do you get all the cell
types to the correct place?

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:34.200
And how are they put into
the correct structure?

00:14:56.180 --> 00:15:00.080
Let's phrase the problem
by looking at the kidney.

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:05.690
The kidney is one of
the most complex organs.

00:15:05.690 --> 00:15:07.050
It does two things.

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:10.400
It filters the blood and
gets waste products out

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:12.860
of the blood,
particularly products

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:15.810
of amino acid metabolism.

00:15:15.810 --> 00:15:18.830
And it also maintains
water balance.

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:20.780
Both of those things
are crucial functions

00:15:20.780 --> 00:15:25.220
of that kidney, which consists
of about 15 different cell

00:15:25.220 --> 00:15:29.210
types, which are connected
into several types of tubes

00:15:29.210 --> 00:15:32.010
that lead on fluidly
from one to the next.

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:34.730
You have one type of
tube that does one thing.

00:15:34.730 --> 00:15:36.560
It's connected to
the next tube, which

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:40.220
does the next thing, connected
to the next tube and so on.

00:15:40.220 --> 00:15:42.020
The tubes are very long.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:44.120
They form a 3-D organization.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:46.760
And they form filtration
units, called nephrons.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:48.890
Here are part of the nephrons.

00:15:48.890 --> 00:15:51.860
And you just have to look at
this without any knowledge

00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:54.080
to see that this is
a complex structure.

00:15:57.150 --> 00:16:01.120
This is a distant view, so
you can't see the cells here.

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:03.450
Low magnification structure.

00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:05.460
This is a really complex organ.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:09.810
And it takes a moment's
thought to wonder how something

00:16:09.810 --> 00:16:11.830
like this gets put together.

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:14.360
And, of course, this is not
only important for developments.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.160
It's important for thinking
about how you would replace

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:20.510
someone's kidney with
something that was artificial,

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:24.130
and not just using
donated organs.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:26.460
Could you build
something like a kidney

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:30.640
and use it in place
of donated organs?

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:33.960
So the question of organogenesis
is of huge importance

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:38.130
both to basic researches,
to physicians trying

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:41.100
to understand what goes
wrong when organs fail,

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:44.310
and to bioengineers who are
trying to build organs that

00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:45.660
would replace human versions.

00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:51.510
Let's start by tackling
the first question.

00:16:51.510 --> 00:16:56.520
How do you put different cell
types in the correct place?

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:58.860
And there are three
possibilities, all of which

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:00.080
are used by the body.

00:17:19.790 --> 00:17:23.460
OK, so one, they can move there.

00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:26.500
There can be all these cell
types all over the body.

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:29.490
And they can say, oh, OK,
we need to go move over here

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:31.630
to build a kidney.

00:17:31.630 --> 00:17:34.780
OK, it seems unlikely,
but in fact, it's true.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:40.240
And that process
would be migration,

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:43.090
where the cells come
from all over the place

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:44.800
to build the organ.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:46.645
The cells need to
know where to go.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:57.090
And that just pushes
the problem back one.

00:17:57.090 --> 00:18:01.650
But the great example of
cell migration is the limb.

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:04.500
Most of the cells in
your limbs and mine

00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:07.800
did not come right from
where the limb grew.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.380
They migrated there
from the spinal cord.

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:12.360
They migrated there
from the muscles

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:14.880
on the sides of the body.

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:18.360
And the blood vessels also
grew in from the cells

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:20.450
that were distant.

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:28.030
So the limb puts it all
together by moving cells around.

00:18:28.030 --> 00:18:30.480
How else could you get
cells to the right place?

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:38.710
See, it's not so easy.

00:18:38.710 --> 00:18:40.710
OK, so here's another one.

00:18:40.710 --> 00:18:45.240
Well, you could in one place
tell a bunch of different cells

00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:47.710
to form at the same time.

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:50.080
You could have your
organ and say, all right,

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:53.790
we need cell types 1 to 10.

00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:54.710
Form.

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:55.780
Here's some signals.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:57.730
You will form in this one place.

00:18:57.730 --> 00:18:59.620
And in fact that happens.

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:06.340
This is called
co-induction, where

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:17.040
many cell types or several
cell types form in one place,

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:23.550
often because one signal can
act at different concentrations

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:26.010
to give rise to
different cell types.

00:19:26.010 --> 00:19:28.980
So many cell types
form in one place,

00:19:28.980 --> 00:19:37.980
often due to a concentration
gradient of an inducer,

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:38.505
of a signal.

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:56.400
And the great example of this is
the spinal cord, and the nerves

00:19:56.400 --> 00:20:01.260
in the spinal cord, which arise
by co-induction of actually

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:05.060
about two different inducers.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:10.580
And the third one is called
sequential induction.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:19.540
And this is how
the kidneys forms,

00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:22.180
where the idea with
sequential induction

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:24.760
is that a cell type forms.

00:20:24.760 --> 00:20:28.780
And it says, OK, I need this
other cell type to work with.

00:20:28.780 --> 00:20:30.670
And it instructs
the cells around

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:32.680
to become another cell type.

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:35.890
And those cells in turn might
instruct some cells around them

00:20:35.890 --> 00:20:37.690
to become another cell type.

00:20:37.690 --> 00:20:39.370
And there's this
conversation going

00:20:39.370 --> 00:20:43.870
on sequentially in the place
where the organ will form.

00:20:43.870 --> 00:20:56.590
So cell type 1
induces or signals

00:20:56.590 --> 00:21:07.390
to type 2, which
induces type 3, etc.

00:21:07.390 --> 00:21:12.730
And a great example
of this is the kidney,

00:21:12.730 --> 00:21:17.470
where I will say it is still not
known how you build a kidney.

00:21:17.470 --> 00:21:18.970
Some of the steps
are understood.

00:21:18.970 --> 00:21:20.920
But there's no
organ where we can

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:23.080
say these are all the
steps that build the organ.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:24.160
It's incredibly complex.

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:30.460
Good.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:33.340
That's all I'm going to say
about organogenesis, to throw

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:35.860
out at your this
complex problem.

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:38.920
And you can explore it
more in later courses.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.460
I am going to talk more, though,
about this question of 3D

00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:43.150
structure.

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:50.772
And that is the question
of morphogenesis.

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:02.740
Oranogenesis,
morphogenesis, you might

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:06.220
have heard of histogenesis,
which means building tissues.

00:22:06.220 --> 00:22:09.160
The genesis part
refers to building.

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:12.700
That's what it means,
building of something.

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:21.040
Morphogenesis, building a
three-dimensional structure,

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:31.570
or the generation of
form is what you'll see.

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:37.320
And what that really means
is building 3D structure.

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:46.880
And this relates
to organogenesis

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:49.400
because in organogenesis
one of the things that's

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:52.670
hidden on the board
above was the question

00:22:52.670 --> 00:23:01.453
of getting cells of an organ
into the correct 3D structure.

00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:16.380
And, of course, this
question of 3D structure

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:18.930
is intuitively quite clear.

00:23:18.930 --> 00:23:22.740
You can imagine a
human heart or having

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:25.260
some kind of animal's
heart in front of you.

00:23:25.260 --> 00:23:27.210
It's an extraordinary structure.

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:29.930
It's actually a folded tube,
where the walls of the tube

00:23:29.930 --> 00:23:31.780
have become very muscular.

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:35.100
And the heart will pump
with great regularity.

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:38.700
It's a controlled pump that can
speed up or slow down depending

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:42.320
on the how the animal is doing.

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:47.240
And that heart contains about
10 different kinds of cells.

00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:49.940
And you can imagine having
one in front of you.

00:23:49.940 --> 00:23:51.860
And you can imagine
my coming along

00:23:51.860 --> 00:23:54.890
with some kind of
protease or calcium

00:23:54.890 --> 00:23:58.010
free medium that will cause
the cells of the heart

00:23:58.010 --> 00:24:02.490
to leave one
another, deconstruct

00:24:02.490 --> 00:24:03.760
the structure of the heart.

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:06.510
Now you've got a heart
that's not this pump looking

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:07.920
tube structure.

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:09.840
It's a pile of cells.

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:13.552
The same cells that were in
the organ of the heart, but,

00:24:13.552 --> 00:24:14.510
of course, they're not.

00:24:14.510 --> 00:24:16.110
They're just a pile of cells.

00:24:16.110 --> 00:24:16.950
They're all there.

00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:18.780
They might all be alive.

00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:20.370
But they're not acting.

00:24:20.370 --> 00:24:22.780
And that's really an
engineering problem,

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:24.790
which is what
morphogenesis is all about.

00:24:24.790 --> 00:24:27.390
And I want to just discuss
morphogenesis with you

00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:33.180
because I think as a science
and engineering problem,

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:36.100
it's really an extraordinary
one to think about.

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:38.880
And it's extraordinary to think
about because really there's

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:41.550
only one building
material by which all

00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:46.440
the structures of all organisms
are built. And that's cells.

00:24:46.440 --> 00:24:49.650
You can't find different
plastics or different metals

00:24:49.650 --> 00:24:52.410
or different alloys
to build things with,

00:24:52.410 --> 00:24:54.420
it's just one building material.

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:56.940
And it's really
amazing what life

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.130
has managed to do with cells.

00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:02.290
And that's what we'll explore
for the rest of the lecture.

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:06.540
So getting cells in organs
into the correct 3D structure.

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:16.500
This is a great example of
3D structure, another one,

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:21.540
the lungs, which are about a
20-fold iteration of branching.

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:25.470
You start off with one
tube, the trachea, which

00:25:25.470 --> 00:25:28.200
branches into the two bronchi.

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:31.470
And those branch and they
branch and they branch.

00:25:31.470 --> 00:25:33.900
It's about a 20-fold branching.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:37.020
And you end up with
many, many little tubes.

00:25:37.020 --> 00:25:39.850
In this rendition,
the ends of the tubes,

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:42.660
which are sacs of cells,
have been taken away.

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:45.870
But it's through these tubes
that oxygen moves or air moves.

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:49.140
The oxygen is extracted
from the air, moves

00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:54.090
into the bloodstream, and
then the waste air is exhaled.

00:25:54.090 --> 00:25:55.530
And the same thing starts again.

00:25:55.530 --> 00:25:59.190
How do you build these lungs
with this branching arrangement

00:25:59.190 --> 00:25:59.774
of cells?

00:25:59.774 --> 00:26:01.440
And indeed, how do
you build the kidney?

