00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:54.210
But cells, you
know, are not just

00:31:54.210 --> 00:31:57.000
equivalent to bricks one shape.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:58.500
They can actually change.

00:31:58.500 --> 00:32:00.910
So it's not quite fair
that I said to you

00:32:00.910 --> 00:32:02.460
this is different
than engineering

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:04.440
where you've only
got one material.

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:06.850
It's true you've only
got one material.

00:32:06.850 --> 00:32:07.860
But it can change.

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:11.130
It can change its shape,
and it can move around.

00:32:11.130 --> 00:32:14.640
And the two kinds of things
you really need to know

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:21.935
are involved are single
cells and cell sheets.

00:32:26.240 --> 00:32:29.905
And single cells and cell sheets
are interchangeable from one

00:32:29.905 --> 00:32:30.405
another.

00:32:33.180 --> 00:32:35.875
Single cells are also
called mesenchyme.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:42.320
[INAUDIBLE] [? they ?] are.

00:32:42.320 --> 00:32:43.190
Single cell.

00:32:47.020 --> 00:32:52.920
And groups of mesenchymal
cells can associate

00:32:52.920 --> 00:32:55.215
to become sheets of cells.

00:33:00.840 --> 00:33:04.590
And these sheets are
called epithelia,

00:33:04.590 --> 00:33:06.480
or singular is epithelium.

00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:13.570
Single cells migrate.

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:14.095
They move.

00:33:17.780 --> 00:33:20.600
And there are no junctions
between the cells that

00:33:20.600 --> 00:33:23.930
allows them to be single cells.

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:27.650
Epithelia, cell sheets,
can change shape.

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:30.890
But they don't move
around that much.

00:33:30.890 --> 00:33:38.570
So they change shape as sheets.

00:33:41.720 --> 00:33:47.115
And what that allows them to do
is to form coverings and tubes.

00:33:55.410 --> 00:33:58.110
I should say one
very important thing.

00:33:58.110 --> 00:34:00.330
The process is reversible.

00:34:00.330 --> 00:34:04.050
If you look at the next handout,
there is more information

00:34:04.050 --> 00:34:05.414
that you'll get.

00:34:12.239 --> 00:34:14.530
Here's your epithelial sheet.

00:34:14.530 --> 00:34:16.320
It's joined together
by junctions.

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:19.020
Let me make a note
that there are

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:21.690
junctions between the cells.

00:34:21.690 --> 00:34:25.093
That's what sticks the
cells together is a sheet.

00:34:25.093 --> 00:34:26.469
Here are the junctions.

00:34:26.469 --> 00:34:28.020
There are two kind.

00:34:28.020 --> 00:34:30.420
There's top ones
called tight junctions,

00:34:30.420 --> 00:34:32.014
which are waterproof junctions.

00:34:32.014 --> 00:34:33.389
And then they
these are the ones,

00:34:33.389 --> 00:34:35.535
called adhesion junctions,
which aren't so strong.

00:34:38.340 --> 00:34:44.100
Both epithelia and mesenchyme
sit on the extracellular

00:34:44.100 --> 00:34:48.900
matrix, or ECM, which
we mentioned way back,

00:34:48.900 --> 00:34:53.340
glycoproteins that are involved
in giving support and also

00:34:53.340 --> 00:34:56.800
carrying signaling
molecules to cells.

00:34:56.800 --> 00:35:00.840
And here is the conversion of
the sheet to the single cells,

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:03.480
and the single cells
back to the sheet.

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:07.950
This process of epithelial
mesenchymal transition

00:35:07.950 --> 00:35:10.920
or mesenchymal
epithelial transition

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:13.260
is very important in cancer.

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:15.480
Tumors usually start
off as epithelia.

00:35:15.480 --> 00:35:18.030
The And they become metastatic.

00:35:18.030 --> 00:35:20.140
They disperse
throughout the body

00:35:20.140 --> 00:35:22.290
when they become mesenchymal,
or when they give off

00:35:22.290 --> 00:35:25.230
single cells, which can
migrate and establish

00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:26.430
the tumor somewhere else.

00:35:26.430 --> 00:35:30.120
So this process is crucial
both in building organs

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:32.700
and in cancer biology.

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:34.410
The other thing that
you should note--

00:35:34.410 --> 00:35:36.510
we're not going to
dwell on it very much--

00:35:36.510 --> 00:35:40.500
is that the cells in a
sheet have got orientation.

00:35:40.500 --> 00:35:43.590
They've got an axis of
asymmetry along one side,

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:47.730
call the apical basal axis
and an axis of asymmetry

00:35:47.730 --> 00:35:50.550
along the top, called
the planar axis.

00:35:50.550 --> 00:35:53.900
But we're not going to
dwell on that very much.

00:35:53.900 --> 00:36:03.950
All right, let's look
what epithelial sheets

00:36:03.950 --> 00:36:06.390
do in a little more detail.

00:36:06.390 --> 00:36:18.420
So epithelial sheets or
epithelial form waterproof

00:36:18.420 --> 00:36:20.070
coverings, as I've noted.

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:30.210
And through cell shape changes,
they'll also bend a cell sheet

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:31.710
or turn it into a tube.

00:36:44.320 --> 00:36:48.460
And they do this by a series
of stereotypical changes,

00:36:48.460 --> 00:37:01.220
where cells can change shape,
so that kind of a square cell

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:09.410
can become an elongated cell in
one direction or a cell that's

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:12.320
elongated in a
different direction.

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:19.230
Or it can become a
wedge shaped cell.

00:37:19.230 --> 00:37:21.720
And the names of these
different kinds of cells

00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:23.130
don't really matter.

00:37:23.130 --> 00:37:24.330
And they're not sequential.

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:28.080
So this cell can
become this cell.

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:34.240
It can also become this wedge
shaped cell in one fell swoop.

00:37:34.240 --> 00:37:37.500
But if you think about it,
these changes in cell shape

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:38.950
can do lots of things.

00:37:38.950 --> 00:37:42.462
For example, if cells
get long and thin,

00:37:42.462 --> 00:37:45.630
then the cell sheet
will lengthen.

00:37:45.630 --> 00:37:48.390
If cells get wedge shaped,
and you've got a whole bunch

00:37:48.390 --> 00:37:51.240
of them getting wedge shaped--
you can draw this out--

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:53.820
you'll actually
bend the cell sheet.

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:54.450
Draw it out.

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:56.721
Put a whole bunch of wedge
shaped cells next to one

00:37:56.721 --> 00:37:57.220
another.

00:37:57.220 --> 00:38:00.180
And you'll see there's no
way you can get a flat sheet.

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:02.400
The cell sheet bends.

00:38:02.400 --> 00:38:04.500
And that is one of
the things which

00:38:04.500 --> 00:38:07.630
drives building the
structure of organs.

00:38:15.100 --> 00:38:17.860
There are a lot of different
ways to make tubes.

00:38:17.860 --> 00:38:19.970
I've diagrammed them
on the next few slides.

00:38:19.970 --> 00:38:21.220
You don't have these.

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:24.280
Cell sheets can roll
up to form a tube.

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:27.670
Mesenchymal cells can
condense, can come together,

00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:29.580
to form a tube.

00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:31.810
And here's a really
extraordinary one.

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:33.880
Single cells can form tubes.

00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:37.300
Tiny, single cells with
a 10 micron diameter

00:38:37.300 --> 00:38:39.960
can roll up on their
cell themselves

00:38:39.960 --> 00:38:42.250
or actually hollow
out their middles

00:38:42.250 --> 00:38:44.050
to become tiny, tiny tubes.

00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:53.070
What about single cells?

00:38:53.070 --> 00:38:55.380
Single cells move.

00:38:55.380 --> 00:38:59.540
And this allows
things to sort out

00:38:59.540 --> 00:39:02.720
and cells to get to
where they need to go.

00:39:02.720 --> 00:39:04.970
But we're also going
to use this property

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:07.790
to understand the
molecular principles that

00:39:07.790 --> 00:39:09.590
underlies cell shape change.

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:11.100
And that you should know.

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:20.220
Let's make a note
that single cells move

00:39:20.220 --> 00:39:33.520
and that this allows cells to
sort and tissues and organs

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:34.180
to form.

00:39:38.050 --> 00:39:40.615
And then what I'm going to tell
you over the next few slides

00:39:40.615 --> 00:39:44.920
and on your handouts is that
all of the movement and all

00:39:44.920 --> 00:39:48.130
of these shape changes
that I drew on the board

00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:52.330
have got to do with changing
the cytoskeleton of the cell.

00:39:52.330 --> 00:39:55.090
But what I'll tell
you is that it's

00:39:55.090 --> 00:39:58.450
about locally changing
the cytoskeleton,

00:39:58.450 --> 00:40:01.300
where you have to stop
viewing the cell as something

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:04.540
huge, where independent
things can happen

00:40:04.540 --> 00:40:06.610
in different parts of the cell.

00:40:06.610 --> 00:40:10.270
And those independent
changes in the structure,

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:13.150
in the skeleton of the
cell will get the cell

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:19.880
to become long or squat
or wedge shaped or moved.

00:40:19.880 --> 00:40:30.800
So shape and movement of
both sheets and single cells

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:37.050
is controlled by changing
the cytoskeleton.

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:53.620
But it's done so locally, which
means in one part of the cell.

00:40:58.030 --> 00:41:03.010
And a most important change
that occurs as the cytoskeleton

00:41:03.010 --> 00:41:06.400
changes or with cytoskeletal
changes or is cytoskeletal

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:16.130
change is a polymerization
of actin from G-actin,

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:26.120
which is unpolymerized,
to F-actin--

00:41:26.120 --> 00:41:28.610
and this is reversible--

00:41:28.610 --> 00:41:33.530
which is polymerized,
non-covalently.

00:41:33.530 --> 00:41:39.590
And this F-actin
will stretch the cell

00:41:39.590 --> 00:41:41.900
and help the cell to move.

00:41:41.900 --> 00:41:45.200
And let's explore
that in this movie

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:47.330
and in the rest
of your handouts.

00:41:47.330 --> 00:41:51.530
This is a movie of a
cell, where the actin has

00:41:51.530 --> 00:41:54.650
been labeled fluorescently.

00:41:54.650 --> 00:41:57.470
And what you can see
as the cell is moving

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:01.080
are these little
filaments of bright green.

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:04.050
Those are the
polymerized F-actin.

00:42:04.050 --> 00:42:07.620
And you can see if you just
focus on one, over the course

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:10.920
of minutes, it goes away.

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:12.960
And new ones form.

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:15.960
And the new ones are
forming in the direction

00:42:15.960 --> 00:42:18.330
that the cell is moving.

00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:21.850
And this movie really
illustrates the principles

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:26.760
underlying how the
cytoskeleton is controlled.

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:28.410
Let's draw something
on the board

00:42:28.410 --> 00:42:30.600
or let's write a few
things on the board

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:33.330
and then look at your
last two handouts.

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:37.120
And what you'll understand is
that the principles governing

00:42:37.120 --> 00:42:41.890
actin polymerization are really
the same for both single cells

00:42:41.890 --> 00:42:44.450
and for cell sheets.

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:59.710
The idea here is that the
extracellular matrix, the ECM,

00:42:59.710 --> 00:43:16.245
connects to the plasma membrane
via receptors on the plasma

00:43:16.245 --> 00:43:16.745
membrane.

00:43:23.510 --> 00:43:26.150
When ligands bind
these receptors,

00:43:26.150 --> 00:43:27.710
you know what happens now.

00:43:27.710 --> 00:43:30.150
Signal transduction
is activated.

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:37.880
So the ligands plus
the receptors--

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:46.690
and there are many
different signaling pathways

00:43:46.690 --> 00:43:49.270
that can be involved--

00:43:49.270 --> 00:43:53.170
go and activate a
cascade of things,

00:43:53.170 --> 00:44:10.070
which involve kinases, a
signal cascade via kinases

00:44:10.070 --> 00:44:12.980
and via special GTPase.

00:44:12.980 --> 00:44:18.095
Remember Ras was a GTPase,
but this one is called Rho.

00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:33.540
And Rho GPTase it's
critical in telling G-actin

00:44:33.540 --> 00:44:36.920
to polymerize and form F-actin.

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:41.710
And so out of this
the Rho GPTase

00:44:41.710 --> 00:44:47.510
tells G-actin to form F actin.

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:50.370
And with that,
various things happen.

00:44:50.370 --> 00:44:57.440
So let's look at
your last handouts.

00:44:57.440 --> 00:45:00.250
Here's the cell migrating.

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:02.590
And the thing that
I want you to see

00:45:02.590 --> 00:45:05.990
is that in the
direction of migration,

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:10.660
there are receptors that
are bound to ligands.

00:45:10.660 --> 00:45:13.030
Signal transduction
has occurred.

00:45:13.030 --> 00:45:15.360
I've diagrammed it down here.

00:45:15.360 --> 00:45:17.620
And F-actin, these
little filaments,

00:45:17.620 --> 00:45:22.060
have formed in the direction
in which the cell is moving.

00:45:22.060 --> 00:45:26.110
And where the cell is
detaching so that the cell can

00:45:26.110 --> 00:45:28.720
move forwards-- you have to
lift up your foot in order

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:29.500
to move forward.

00:45:29.500 --> 00:45:31.480
It's the same thing
with the cell--

00:45:31.480 --> 00:45:35.110
where the cell is moving
forward, they're no ligands.

00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:37.720
And there's no F-actin.

00:45:37.720 --> 00:45:43.120
That principle is
crucial also in changing

00:45:43.120 --> 00:45:44.410
cell shape and sheets.

00:45:44.410 --> 00:45:46.420
It's a little more complicated.

00:45:46.420 --> 00:45:53.650
But, again, there are receptors
that interact with Rho GPTases,

00:45:53.650 --> 00:45:56.560
change the cytoskeleton
and cell sheets

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:59.540
and change the shape
of the cell sheets.

00:45:59.540 --> 00:46:02.050
And this is really the
molecular underpinning

00:46:02.050 --> 00:46:07.210
that will get those single cells
to form tubes and bench sheets

00:46:07.210 --> 00:46:10.480
and all of the materials that
are needed to build organs.

00:46:10.480 --> 00:46:12.660
And we'll stop there.

